</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,150,1905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1807,1833]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name expresses great overall similarity of these apionines to the attelabid subfamily 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Attelabidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Rhynchitinae">Rhynchitinae</taxonomicName>
, to which they have been frequently assigned in some provisionally sorted museum collections. Gender neuter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
